* .NET Core Version: release/5.0 branch (af41134ff98cf2793a2fcf40f21f95dc94f3ee79), includes #4222

* Have you experienced this same bug with .NET Framework?: No. The problem is also not in .NET Core 3.1.

**Problem description:**

When adding a image to the ImageList, the entire contents of a ListView that is using that ImageList is redrawn. This causes it flicker and if there are enough item, it slows down the app. This seems to be causes by the fix in #4222. Every time an image is added to an image list, the `ImageList.RecreateHandle` event is raised. This causes the ListView to call `ImageList.CreateUniqueHandle`, which always creates a copy of the native image list.

**Expected behavior:**

I think to prevent the redrawing the `ImageList` needs to share the underlying native image list with the `ListView`, instead of giving it a new copy every time an image is added. This would prevent the `ListView` from redrawing unnecessarily.

I know y'all recently change the lifetime management in #3601 to fix some crashes, so I understand this might not be an easy fix.

**Minimal repro:**

```c#
using System;
using System.Drawing;
using System.Windows.Forms;

class MyForm : Form
{
    [STAThread]
    static void Main()
    {
        Application.SetHighDpiMode(HighDpiMode.SystemAware);
        Application.EnableVisualStyles();
        Application.SetCompatibleTextRenderingDefault(false);
        Application.Run(new MyForm());
    }

    ListView lv;
    ImageList il;
    Timer tmr;

    MyForm()
    {
        tmr = new Timer
        {
            Interval = 100,
        };
        il = new ImageList()
        {
        };
        lv = new ListView()
        {
            LargeImageList = il,
            View = View.LargeIcon,
            Dock = DockStyle.Fill,
        };
        this.Controls.Add(lv);

        var red = new Bitmap(il.ImageSize.Width, il.ImageSize.Height);
        using (var g = Graphics.FromImage(red))
            g.Clear(Color.Red);
        int redIndex = il.Images.Add(red, Color.Transparent);

        for (int i = 0; i < 1000; i++)
        {
            var lvi = new ListViewItem(i.ToString(), redIndex);
            lv.Items.Add(lvi);
        }

        this.WindowState = FormWindowState.Maximized;
        this.Load += MyForm_Load;
        tmr.Tick += Tmr_Tick;
    }

    private void MyForm_Load(object sender, EventArgs e)
    {
        tmr.Enabled = true;
    }

    private void Tmr_Tick(object sender, EventArgs e)
    {
        il.Images.Add(new Bitmap(il.ImageSize.Width, il.ImageSize.Height), Color.Transparent);
    }
}

```

* .NET Core Version: **5.0.100** and **3.1.404**
* Windows version: **Windows 10** (18363.1139)
* Does the bug reproduce also in WPF for .NET Framework 4.8?: **No**
* Is this bug related specifically to tooling in Visual Studio (e.g. XAML Designer, Code editing, etc...)? **No**

 **Problem description:**
 
Calls to `comctl32.dll` succeed in .NET Framework 4.8, but fail in .NET 5 and also in .NET Core 3.1 with a `System.EntryPointNotFoundException`.

e.g.

```csharp
[DllImport("comctl32.dll", PreserveSig = false)]
private static extern void TaskDialogIndirect([In] ref TaskDialogConfig pTaskConfig, out int pnButton,
    out int pnRadioButton, [MarshalAs(UnmanagedType.Bool)] out bool pfVerificationFlagChecked);

// ...

var config = new TaskDialogConfig
{
    pszWindowTitle = "Task dialog title",
    pszMainInstruction = "Task dialog main instruction",
    dwCommonButtons = TaskDialogCommonButtonFlags.OkButton | TaskDialogCommonButtonFlags.CancelButton,
    // ...
};

using (new ComCtlv6ActivationContext(enable: true))
{
    TaskDialogIndirect(ref config, out _, out _, out _);
}
```

 **Actual behavior:**

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/177608/99158014-8d2d9980-26a4-11eb-95c9-8ecd3e366fff.png)

```
System.EntryPointNotFoundException: Unable to find an entry point named 'TaskDialogIndirect' in DLL 'comctl32.dll'.
   at TaskDialogApi.TaskDialog.TaskDialogIndirect(TaskDialogConfig& pTaskConfig, Int32& pnButton, Int32& pnRadioButton, Boolean& pfVerificationFlagChecked)
```
 
 **Expected behavior:**
 
Display the Task Dialog requested

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/177608/99158064-22309280-26a5-11eb-9d4a-fa7b5a58d6a5.png)

